So, I couldn't understand when You mentioned us reimplementing the transcoding as well as manipulation of input/output streams.

And extract pixel data is just an option in the test program and nothing to do with the transcoding. However give me couple of days to get back to You with the truncated code.

> Please find the test code inside "uca-convert.zip". You can find the main class at com.iso.uca.dicom.convert.UcaConvertApp. As the program was using our internal maven modules earlier, I had to bring the code from those respective modules to main class. So, apologies in advance for having all code in one class.
> 
> Please find below the command line arguments I used in my test "--ints 1.2.840.10008.1.2.1 --outts 1.2.840.10008.1.2.4.70 input-directory output-directory"
> 
> --outts is the output/target transfer syntax --ints means that the program will only convert the instance when its in this transfer syntax.
> 
> So, my use case was to convert LE to JPEGLossless. And for other instances with different compressed transfer syntaxes, the program will automatically try to decompress those in memory in order to validate the compression.
> 
> You can find the code for above functionality in method "toTransferSyntax(Path inputFile, Path outputFile)"
> 
> Please let me know if You face any issue.
> 
> [uca-convert.zip](https://github.com/dcm4che/dcm4che/files/13050631/uca-convert.zip)

I had a quick look at the code and there are a lot of problems in it. The most important is the default use of the legacy transcoding implementation, which contains a long list of problems (with a native implementation that hasn't been updated since 2006).

I think it's definitely not a good idea to have modified the transcoding part of dcm4che in more than 1000 lines of code, while if you use weasis-dicom-tools you can have more transcoding parameters in less than 10 lines of code:
```java
    String tsuid = UID.JPEGLSLossless;
    Path in = Paths.get("test/img/input");
    Path out =  Paths.get("test/img/output");

    DicomTranscodeParam params = new DicomTranscodeParam(tsuid);
    try {
      Files.createDirectories(out);
      Transcoder.dcm2dcm(in, out, params);
    } catch (IOException e) {
      throw new RuntimeException(e);
    }
```
To follow up on this problem, please only post code that is limited to using dcm4che or weasis-dicom-tools and that does not reimplement transcoding, extract pixel data, manipulate inputstream or ouptutstream...

@rahulgulati1986 Before coming to the conclusion of a memory leak, it is important to provide reproducible test code, as there are situations where there may be intensive memory usage.

As far as multiframes are concerned, the implementation in dcm4che is not optimal in my opinion. You could try using the weasis-dicom-tools API (see this [message](https://github.com/dcm4che/dcm4che/pull/1324#issuecomment-1626891799)), which manages each multiframe independently and, in some cases, facilitates memory release.

There is also a [modification](https://github.com/dcm4che/dcm4che/pull/1345) in the next release 5.31.1 which unifies the implementation through native memory release for the different Java versions.
